## REVIEW

## Methylene blue can increase the/uni00A0number of/uni00A0lymph nodes harvested in/uni00A0colorectal cancer: a/uni00A0meta-analysis

Jianlin/uni00A0Xiao 1 /uni00A0· Yu/uni00A0Shen 1 /uni00A0· Xuyang/uni00A0Yang 1 /uni00A0· Mingtian/uni00A0Wei 1 /uni00A0· Wenjian/uni00A0Meng 1 /uni00A0· Ziqiang/uni00A0Wang 1

Accepted: 8 January 2023 / Published online: 18 February 2023 © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature 2023

## Abstract

Aim The lymph node (LN) status plays an important role in colorectal cancer (CRC), which depends on adequate LN harvest. In some studies, methylene blue has been used to increase the number of LNs harvested in/uni00A0vitro. The purpose was to evaluate the effect of methylene blue staining on LN harvest during radical resection of CRC.

Result Of 328 articles found, a meta-analysis was conducted of 15 studies (2 randomized controlled trials and 13 nonrandomized controlled trials) composed of 3104 patients. Meta-analysis showed that methylene blue could not only significantly increase the number of LNs harvested in CRC specimens (stained group 28.23 vs unstained group 16.15; weighted mean difference 12.08; 95% CI, 8.03-16.12; p < 0.001; I 2 = 95%), but also reduce the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested (methylene blue-stained group 7.91% vs unstained group 30.90%; OR 0.12; 95% CI, 0.05-0.26; p < 0.001; I 2 = 78%).

Methods The Cochrane Library, MEDLINE, Embase, PubMed, and Web of Science were searched from the dates of inception until 15 October 2022. Studies were included if they were randomized controlled trials or nonrandomized controlled trials for radical resection of rectal cancer according to the principle of total mesorectal excision that compared the use of methylene blue with blank control in LN harvest. The primary outcomes were the number of LNs harvested and the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested.

Conclusion Methylene blue can increase the number of LNs harvested in CRC, reduce the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested, and ensure the accuracy of LN staging.

Keywords Methylene blue/uni00A0· Colorectal cancer/uni00A0· Lymph node

## Introduction

Colorectal cancer (CRC) is one of the leading causes of cancer morbidity and mortality worldwide [1]. In CRC, lymph node (LN) status often plays an important role both in distinguishing patients with stage II and stage III disease and in determining the need for the potential benefit from adjuvant therapy [2]. The higher the number of positive metastatic LNs and the higher pathological stage, the worse the prognosis of the patients [3, 4]. According to the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) and the Union for International Cancer Control, and the College of American

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

Pathologists (CAP), a minimum number of 12 LNs should be examined in all CRC surgical specimens to maximize the identification of regional LN metastases [5].

The aim of our study was to perform a meta-analysis to assess whether methylene blue (MB) could increase the number of LNs harvested and reduce the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested in CRC.

In recent years, neoadjuvant therapy has been gradually used in daily practice. Compared with postoperative radiotherapy and chemotherapy, neoadjuvant therapy can significantly improve local control of CRC [6]. However, the proportion of cases in which fewer than 12 investigable LNs were obtained in colorectal preparations after neoadjuvant therapy has been stated by various authors as lying between 10 and 80% [7-9]. At present, some techniques such as fat clearance, immunohistochemical analysis, and sentinel LN technique have been developed to improve LN retrieval and accuracy of staging [10, 11].

## Methods (PRISMA guideline)

## Study design

This review conforms to the AMSTAR 2 checklist [12] and also complies with the PRISMA checklist [13]. A review protocol was produced and set out the process to address the study objectives.

## Search strategy

The Cochrane Library, MEDLINE, Embase, PubMed, and Web of Science were searched on 15 October 2022. The search terms include 'methylene blue,' 'MB,' 'rectal tumor,' 'rectal cancer,' 'colon tumor,' 'colon cancer,' 'CRC,' 'colorectal surgery,' and 'LN.' Then, the references of all relevant studies were checked to find other articles that may be included. The syntax construction and database search were performed in collaboration with a medical librarian who specialized in conducting systematic reviews. Studies comparing MB staining and blank control were included. There was no limit on the date of publication. Studies were first evaluated for inclusion based on title and abstract by 2 independent researchers (Jianlin Xiao and Yu Shen) and finally evaluated independently based on full text. Differences in article selection were discussed, and articles were included or excluded after reaching an agreement. Studies were included if they met the following criteria: (1) studies that compared the number of LNs harvested between the MB-stained group and unstained group in patients with CRC, (2) studies on the relationship between the use of MB and the number of LNs harvested in patients with CRC. Exclusion criteria were as follows: (1) studies involving surgery for tumors of other organs or CRC data could not be extracted, (2) studies published in non-English, (3) studies using the same database were included only recently published.

## Data collection

Data collection was performed independently by 2 different researchers (Jianlin Xiao and Yu Shen) using standard forms covering study characteristics (study design, year, location, and evidence), patient baseline characteristics (type of intervention, number of patients, age, sex, neoadjuvant therapy, and surgical approach), specimen type, MB use (including dose, staining time, and injection method), the number of LNs harvested, and the number of cases that fewer than 12 LNs harvested.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## Assessment of/uni00A0study quality

Two authors (Jianlin Xiao and Yu Shen) independently used the Cochrane risk-of-bias tool [14] to assess the risk of bias, and methodological quality of included nonrandomized studies was assessed using the Newcastle-Ottawa scale criteria.

## Statistical analysis

The odds ratio (OR) was used to evaluate the raw data extracted from the study and used as summary statistic. The weighted mean difference (WMD) was used to analyze the continuous variables. The 95% confidence interval (CI) is defined as the limit of statistical values. All statistical analysis results were calculated by Review Manager 5.3 software to evaluate the relationship between MB staining and the number of LNs harvested in CRC. At the same time, I 2 test was used to evaluate statistical heterogeneity. OR < 1.0 indicates that the risk of adverse events is lower, and when p < 0.05, it is considered to be statistically significant. When p < 0.05 and I 2 /uni2265 50%, there was significant heterogeneity among the studies. When I 2 < 50%, the fixed effects model is used for statistical analysis. Or the random effects models are used.

## Results

## Search and/uni00A0study characteristics

A PRISMA flow diagram of the complete search strategy is shown in Fig./uni00A01. The initial search resulted in 328 articles (313 after duplicate removal). After screening, 68 articles were selected for full-text reading. After full-text reading, 15 articles were selected for inclusion [15-25, 27-30]. Two articles were randomized controlled trials and 13 were non-randomized controlled trials. A total of 3104 patients were enrolled in the study and were divided into the MB-stained group and the unstained group. All patients underwent CRC surgery following the principle of total mesorectal excision, and some of them received neoadjuvant therapy. Two randomized controlled studies [24, 28] were low bias risk. The remaining 5 retrospective studies [15, 18, 20-22] and 8 prospective studies [16, 17, 19, 23, 25, 27, 29, 30] were moderate bias risk. The summary of the risk of bias assessment is presented in Fig./uni00A02. As shown in Fig./uni00A03, literature included in this meta-analysis is symmetrically distributed in the funnel plots, indicating that there is no significant publication bias.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## Comparison of/uni00A0LNs between/uni00A0the/uni00A0MB-stained and/uni00A0unstained group

The results of the meta-analysis are shown in Table/uni00A01, including 1583 patients in the MB-stained group and 1521 patients in the unstained group. In 2 randomized controlled trials, the average number of LNs harvested was 23.93 in the MB-stained group and 19.71 in the unstained group (WMD = 4.22; 95% CI, 0.85-7.60; p = 0.01; I 2 = 45%). According to 13 other non-randomized controlled trials, the average number of LNs harvested was 28.23 in the MB-stained group and 16.15 in the unstained group (WMD = 12.08; 95% CI, 8.03-16.12; p < 0.001; I 2 = 95%). Compared with the unstained group, the MBstained group could significantly increase the number of LNs harvested (Fig./uni00A04).

In colon cancer patients [18, 24], the average number of LNs harvested was 46.77 in the MB-stained group and 20.49 in the unstained group (WMD 26.29; 95% CI, 15.13-67.72; p < 0.001; I 2 = 93%). In patients with rectal cancer [15, 17, 18, 21, 24, 27], the average number of LNs harvested was

23.16 in the MB-stained group and 12.64 in the unstained group (WMD 11.72; 95% CI, 7.47-15.97; p < 0.001; I 2 = 82%). In addition, some patients received neoadjuvant therapy (the details of these patients were reported in 8 of 15 literature). A total of 459 (35.3%) patients received neoadjuvant therapy in 8 references. According to the 8 references [15, 17, 18, 23, 24, 27, 28, 30], the average number of LNs harvested after neoadjuvant therapy was 26.07 in the MBstained group and 13.25 in the unstained group (95% CI, 7.5-18.11; p < 0.001; I 2 = 91%) (Fig./uni00A05).

Thirteen literatures [15-20, 22-25, 28-30] recorded the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested, 7.91% in the MB-stained group compared with 30.90% in the unstained group, and the difference was statistically significant (OR 0.12; 95% CI, 0.05-0.26; p < 0.001; I 2 = 78%) (Fig./uni00A06). Subgroup analysis showed that the MB-stained group had a lower incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested in patients who received neoadjuvant therapy and those who did not receive neoadjuvant therapy (OR 0.09; 95% CI, 0.02-0.42; p = 0.002; I 2 = 83%/OR 0.01; 95% CI, 0.00-0.07; p < 0.001; I 2 = 28%).

## Discussion

In clinical practice, LN metastasis is an important index to evaluate the recurrence and survival rate of rectal cancer, which is also one of the main bases to determine the

treatment plan for patients with rectal cancer [31-33]. It has been reported that the disease-specific mortality is decreased by 30% in patients with metastatic LNs (stage III) undergoing chemotherapy as the standard adjuvant therapy [34, 35]. Therefore, harvesting enough LNs is

Fig. 3 Funnel plot diagram

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

extremely important to conduct the treatment of CRC (Table/uni00A02).

Methylene blue has excellent permeability and strong binding ability with tissue proteins. It can be stained regardless of whether LNs are involved or not and the diameter of lymphatic vessels. In this meta-analysis, the average number of LNs harvested in the MB-stained group was 12.08 higher than that in the unstained group, and the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested decreased significantly (7.91% vs 30.90%, p < 0.05). It should be noted that for patients who have received neoadjuvant therapy, MB staining reduced the rate of insufficient detection of LNs from 68.01% (185/272) to 23.30% (89/ 382). This proportion seems unsatisfactory for us since 23.30% of

Traditional LN detection relies on visual and touch, which is not only time-consuming but also not completely reliable, and small diameter positive LNs may be omitted [36]. In recent years, preoperative neoadjuvant therapy has been gradually used in the clinic, resulting in the reduction of some tumor lesions and pathological downstaging [37, 38]. However, compared with patients who did not receive neoadjuvant therapy, the average number of LNs in patients receiving neoadjuvant therapy decreased significantly [39]. It often prevents us from obtaining a sufficient number of LNs, and some studies have even found that nearly 60% of patients cannot harvest more than 12 LNs in CRC specimens [40].

the patients who received neoadjuvant therapy still did not find enough LNs after MB staining. However, recently some studies have advocated that a lower yield (LN /uni2265 10) may be adequate for nodal evaluation in rectal cancer patients after neoadjuvant therapy. In addition, because of the large differences in MB staining technology between studies, it is necessary for us to choose a MB staining technology that is more effective and productive.

This study has some limitations. First of all, there are only 2 randomized controlled trials of MB in CRC. Second, most of the published studies are single-center, so selection bias is inevitable. Finally, there is no uniform standard for MB staining technique, and the difference in operation during the test may affect the number of LNs harvested.

Obtaining enough LNs can make LN staging more accurate, although whether these increased LNs will change the pathological LN staging needs further study. Some studies [15, 17, 25, 28] have also pointed out that MB staining mainly increases the number of small LNs (diameter < 5/uni00A0mm), while LNs with diameter < 5/uni00A0mm have a lower probability of metastasis [41].

In conclusion, MB can increase the number of LNs harvested in CRC, reduce the incidence of fewer than 12 LNs harvested, and ensure the accuracy of LN staging. Therefore, we suggest that MB should be applied to the harvest of LN in/uni00A0vitro specimens of CRC.
